==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|rood}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|rōd||a rod, pole, rood (land measure), plot of land of a square rod, a cross, rood (as in Holy-rood), gallows, a cross on which a person is executed, death on a cross, crucifix}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*rōdō}}, {{m|gem-pro|*rōdǭ||rod, pole}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*rōt-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*reh₁t-||bar, beam, stem}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|Rute||rod, cane, pole}}, {{cog|no|roda||rod}}. Largely displaced by {{l|en|cross}}. More at {{l|en|rod}}.

